goals.question: What is the average height of people in the dataset?
goals.rationale: A box plot will help us identify the median, quartiles, and outliers in the height column, giving us a better understanding of the distribution of heights in the dataset.

goals.question: What is the most common name in the dataset?

goals.question: Is there a correlation between age and height in the dataset?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of age and height columns
goals.rationale: A scatter plot will help us identify any correlation between age and height in the dataset, which can be useful in predicting height based on age or vice versa.

goals.question: What is the range of heights for people aged 30 and above?
goals.visualization: Box plot of height column for people aged 30 and above
goals.rationale: A box plot of height for people aged 30 and above will help us identify the median, quartiles, and outliers in the height column for this age group, giving us a better understanding of the distribution of heights for this specific group.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='age', kde=True, color='blue', bins=10)
    plt.axvline(data['age'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2)
    plt.legend(['Median Age: {:.2f}'.format(data['age'].median())])
    plt.title('What is the distribution of ages in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    ax = sns.boxplot(x=data['height'])
    avg_height = data['height'].mean()
    ax.axvline(avg_height, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Average Height: {avg_height:.2f}')
    plt.title('What is the average height of people in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Height (cm)')
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    name_counts = data['name'].value_counts()
    ax = sns.barplot(x=name_counts.index, y=name_counts.values)
    ax.set(xlabel='Name', ylabel='Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the most common name in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data_filtered = data[data['age'] >= 30]
    ax = sns.boxplot(x=data_filtered['height'])
    plt.title("What is the range of heights for people aged 30 and above?", wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
